problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/swap-nodes-in-pairs/description/

Intuition
When i looked at this problem i realized it can be done using pattern in place linked list reversal , now for this question i have to swap pairs , so i am going to swap pairs by reversing 2 nodes then rejoining them and moving forward now the difficulty part for this question is how will i know that a pair exists or there is only one node or the list is empty for that we are going to take a safety dummy node and initally a pointer prev points to this dummy node , now we only swap if prev.next and prev.next.next are present this checks that there are 2 nodes atleast after the prev , now if list is empty or it has only 1 node ,we just return dummy.next as head , now in case there exsists some pairs we are going to need three pointers , left (which points to the node just next to prev) , curr which also points to same node as left , now why are we using 2 pointers that point to same node the reason is , left is use for reconnecting the nodes , where as curr is used for reversing the nodes , During reversal, helper always points to the head of the partially reversed segment. After reversing exactly 2 nodes, the original first node (left) becomes the tail of the swapped pair and is later reconnected to the next part of the list.

Approach
create a safety dummy node pointing towards the head , prev points to dummy node ,
traverse the list while there are 2 nodes available after prev , This is checked using:
prev.next and prev.next.next
For each pair:
Store the first node of the pair in left.
Set curr = left.
Reverse exactly 2 nodes using the standard in-place linked list reversal pattern with a helper pointer.
After reversing:
helper points to the new head of the swapped pair.
left becomes the tail of the swapped pair.
curr points to the first node after the pair.
Reconnect the reversed pair back into the list:
Connect prev to the new head of the reversed pair.
Connect the tail of the reversed pair (left) to the remaining part of the list (curr).
Move prev to left (the tail of the swapped pair) so that it is positioned before the next pair to be processed.
Continue until fewer than two nodes remain, then return dummy.next.

Complexity
Time Complexity: O(n), since each node is processed at most once while traversing and reversing pairs.

Space Complexity: O(1), as the reversal is performed in-place using a constant number of pointers.

Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
class Solution:
    def swapPairs(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        dummy = ListNode(0,head)
        prev = dummy

        while prev.next and prev.next.next:
            left = prev.next
            curr = left

            # swapping nodes / reversing 2 nodes
            helper = None
            for _ in range(2):
                newnode = curr.next
                curr.next = helper
                helper = curr
                curr = newnode
            # reconnecting the nodes
            prev.next = helper
            left.next = curr

            # move prev
            prev = left
        return dummy.next
